## Accessibility Gap by Facility Type

The {{ threshold_m|int }}m threshold reflects DfT guidance on acceptable walking distance to public transport. Beyond this distance, the cognitive and physical burden of the journey to the stop becomes a significant barrier — particularly for elderly residents, those with mobility impairments, and carers with young children.

{% if poi_type and "hospital" in poi_type|lower -%}
NHS hospital access by public transport is a critical equity issue. Patients attending outpatient appointments, those receiving regular treatment (dialysis, chemotherapy), and emergency caregivers face the highest burden when hospitals are inaccessible by bus. The {{ n_beyond_threshold|int|format_thousands }} hospitals beyond {{ threshold_m|int }}m of a stop represent a direct gap between the NHS's expectation of equitable access and transport reality.
{%- elif poi_type and "school" in poi_type|lower -%}
Secondary school access by public transport is a statutory responsibility for LTAs (Education Act 1996, Section 508B). The {{ n_beyond_threshold|int|format_thousands }} schools beyond {{ threshold_m|int }}m represent a legal compliance risk as well as an educational disadvantage for students unable to access school without private car transport.
{%- elif poi_type and "gp" in poi_type|lower or poi_type and "practice" in poi_type|lower -%}
GP surgery accessibility by public transport affects the ability of car-free residents to attend appointments for preventive care, chronic condition management, and urgent consultation. The {{ n_beyond_threshold|int|format_thousands }} practices beyond {{ threshold_m|int }}m contribute to health inequality: lower-income, car-free residents are least able to travel to their GP and most likely to need to.
